To mitigate attacks, OWASP's Threat Modeling involves identifying trust boundaries using STRIDE (Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Denial of Service, Elevation of Privilege, and Information Disclosure). When modeling, consider the attack surface of your application. Use the OWASP ASVS (Application Security Verification Standard) to guide your approach. Identify inputs, outputs, and data storage to ensure secure interactions between components. For example, consider a web service that accepts user input:
```typescript
interface UserInput {
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

const userInput: UserInput = { name: 'John', email: 'john@example.com' };
const validatedInput = validateUserInput(userInput);

// STRIDE considerations:
// Spoofing: Validate email format
// Tampering: Validate input length
// Repudiation: Track input history
// Denial of Service: Rate limit requests
// Elevation of Privilege: Validate user permissions
// Information Disclosure: Sanitize output
```
